SIMPLE: poise
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poise
<hw>Poise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pois</ets>, <ets>peis</ets>, OF. <ets>pois</ets>, <ets>peis</ets>, F. <ets>poids</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pensum</ets> a portion weighed out, <ets>pendere</ets> to weigh, weigh out.  Cf. <er>Avoirdupois</er>, <er>Pendant</er>, <er>Poise</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written also <asp>peise</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Weight; gravity; that which causes a body to descend; heaviness.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Weights of an extraordinary <xex>poise</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>
<-- Obsolete? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The weight, or mass of metal, used in weighing, to
balance the substance weighed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being balanced by equal weight or
power; equipoise; balance; equilibrium; rest.</def>
<rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which causes a balance; a
counterweight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men of unbounded imagination often want the <qex>poise</qex> of
judgment.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a dignified and self-confident manner; graceful
composure and tact in handling difficult social situations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Poise
<hw>Poise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Poised</conjf>, <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Poising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>poisen</ets>,
<ets>peisen</ets>, OF. & F. <ets>peser</ets>, to weigh, balance, OF. il
<ets>peise</ets>, il <ets>poise</ets>, he weighs, F. il
<ets>p⟦egrave⟧se</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pensare</ets>, v. intens. fr.
<ets>pendere</ets> to weigh. See <er>Poise</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Pensive</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written also
<asp>peise</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To balance; to make of equal
weight; <as>as, to <ex>poise</ex> the scales of a
balance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hold or place in equilibrium or
equiponderance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor yet was earth suspended in the sky;⟦br⟧
Nor <qex>poised</qex>, did on her own foundation lie.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To counterpoise; to counterbalance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One scale of reason to <qex>poise</qex> another of sensuality.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>poise</qex> with solid sense a sprightly wit.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To ascertain, as by the balance; to weigh.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He can not sincerely consider the strength, <qex>poise</qex> the
weight, and discern the evidence.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To weigh (down); to oppress.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest leaden slumber <qex>peise</qex> me down to-morrow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Poise
<hw>Poise</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To hang in equilibrium; to be
balanced or suspended; hence, to be in suspense or doubt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The slender, graceful spars⟦br⟧
<qex>Poise</qex> aloft in air.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poiser</ent>⟦br⟧
